(B) The validity and enforceability of the obligations of the Company under the Opinion Documents may be successfully contested by the Company (or its receiver in bankruptcy ()) on the basis of Section 2:7 Dutch Civil Code, if both (i) the execution of the Opinion Documents is not within the scope of the object of the Company () and (ii) the counterparty of the Company under the Opinion Documents knew or ought to have known (without enquiry) of this fact. The Dutch Supreme Court () has ruled that in determining whether the objects of a legal entity are violated, not only the description of such objects in the articles of association is decisive, but all (relevant) circumstances must be taken into account, in particular whether the interests of the legal entity were served by the transaction. As this is largely dependent on factual matters, we are not in a position to opine on this issue. However, in this respect we note that (i) the objects clause () in the Articles allows the entering into by the Company of agreements or documents such as the Opinion Documents, and (ii) although not constituting conclusive evidence thereof, the Board has confirmed in the Board Resolution that it deems the entering into, signing, execution, delivery and performance of the Opinion Documents to be in the Company's corporate interest () and conducive to the realization of and useful in connection with the Company's corporate objects ().
